b'' b'since electrical wiring questions do turn up from time to time on' b"sci.electronics (and the answers aren't always apparent, even to those skilled" b'in electronics), i am hijacking the following faq and posting a copy here.' b"i've asked the writers to cross-post to sci.electronics in the future." b'' b'' b'' b'x-news: cmkrnl news.answers: b'newsgroups: misc.consumers.house,rec.woodworking,news.answers,misc.answers,rec.answers' b'date: apr gmt' b'followup-to: poster' b'expires: may gmt' b'organization: elegant communications inc., ottawa, canada' b'summary: a series of questions and answers about house wiring' b'lines: b'' b'archive-name: electrical-wiring' b'last-modified: sun feb est b'' b'frequently asked questions on electrical wiring' b'' b'' b'comments to (automatic if you reply to this article):' b'' b'this faq is formatted as a digest. most news readers can' b'skip from one question to the next by pressing ^g.' b'' b'answers to many other topics related to houses can be obtained from' b'the misc.consumers.house archive; send an empty piece of mail to' b'' b'changes to previous issue marked with in left column. watch' b'particularly for "new" in the questions list for new or substantively' b'changed answers.' b'' b'note that this is now a registered faq cross-posted to news.answers' b'and should appear in the faq list of lists.' b'' b'' b'introduction/disclaimers' b'what is the nec? where can i get a copy?' b'what is the cec? where can i get a copy?' b'can i do my own wiring? extra pointers?' b'what do i need in the way of tools?' b'what is ul listing?' b'what is csa approval?' b'are there any cheaper, easier to read books on wiring?' b'inspections how and what? why should i get my wiring inspected?' b"my house doesn't meet some of these rules and regulations." b'a word on voltages: b'what does an electrical service look like?' b'what is a circuit?' b'"grounding" versus "grounded" versus "neutral".' b'what does a fuse or breaker do? what are the differences?' b"breakers? can't i use fuses?" b'what size wire should i use?' b'where do these numbers come from?' b'what does mean?' b'what is a "wirenut"/"marrette"/"marr connector". how are they used?' b'what is a gfi/gfci?' b'where should gfcis be used?' b"where shouldn't i use a gfci?" b'what is the difference between a gfci outlet and a gfci breaker?' b"what's the purpose of the ground prong on an outlet, then?" b'why is one prong wider than the other? polarization' b'what kind of outlets do i need in a kitchen?' b'where must outlets and switches be in bathrooms?' b'what is romex/nm/nmd? what is bx? when should i use each?' b'should i use plastic or metal boxes?' b'junction box positioning?' b'can i install a replacement fixture?' b'what does it mean when the lights brighten when a motor starts?' b'what is phase power? should i use it? can i get it in my house?' b'is it better to run motors at or b'what is this nonsense about 3hp on 110v 15a circuits?' b'how do i convert two prong receptacles to three prong?' b'are you sure about gfcis and ungrounded outlets?' b'should the test button work?' b'how should i wire my shop?' b'underground wiring' b'aluminum wiring' b"i'm buying a house! what should i do?" b'what is this weird stuff? old style wiring' b'where do i buy stuff?' b'' b'' b'' b"although we've done a fair bit of wiring, we are not" b'electricians, and we cannot be responsible for what you do. if' b"you're at all uncertain about what is correct or safe, *don't" b'do it*. contact someone qualified a licensed electrician,' b'or your local electrical inspector. electricity is no joke;' b'mistakes can result in shocks, fires, or electrocution.' b'' b'furthermore, our discussion is based on the u.s. national' b'electrical code (nec) and the canadian electrical code (cec).' b'to the best of our abilities, we have confirmed every detail' b"with the electrical code, but we don't quote sections" b"simply to keep this thing readable. if you think we're wrong," b'we invite you to correct us, but please quote references!' b'' b'the nec and the cec do not, in and of themselves, have the' b'force of law. many municipalities adopt it en toto. others,' b'however, do not. check your with your local building' b'department (and <provincial hydro inspection offices in' b'canada) to find out what applies in your area. also,' b'your local electrical utility may also have special requirements' b'for electrical service installation. bear in mind, too, that' b'we say here applies primarily to ordinary single-family' b'residences. multi-family dwellings, mobile homes, commercial' b'establishments, etc., are sometimes governed by different' b'rules.' b'' b'also note that, contrary to popular belief in the u.s. (and in' b'some parts of canada), canada is not a wholly-owned subsidiary' b'of the u.s. consequently, the nec does not apply in canada.' b'lots of things are the same, including voltages, line' b'frequencies, and the laws of physics. but there are a number' b"of crucial differences in the regulations. where we can, we've" b"noted them, flagging the relevant passages with ``nec'' or" b"``cec''." b'' b'remember that the cec and nec are minimal standards. it is often' b'smart to go beyond their minimal requirements.' b'' b'' b'the nec is a model electrical code devised and published by the' b'national fire protection association, an insurance industry group.' b"it's revised every three years. the version has been released." b'you can buy a copy at a decent bookstore, or by calling them directly' b"at the code exists in several versions. there's the" b"full text, which is fairly incomprehensible. there's an abridged" b'edition, which has only the sections likely to apply to most houses.' b"and there's the nec handbook, which contains the ``authorized" b"commentary'' on the code, as well as the full text. that's the" b"recommended version. unfortunately, there's no handbook for" b'the abridged edition. and the full handbook is expensive b'us$65 plus shipping and handling.' b'' b'' b'the canadian standards association is an organization made up' b'of various government agencies, power utilities, insurance' b'companies, electrical manufacturers and other organizations.' b'the csa publishes csa standard c22.1 which is updated every two' b'or three years. each province adopts, with some amendments,' b'this standard and publishes a province-specific code book.' b'since each province publishes its own slightly modified' b'standard, it would be somewhat confusing to obtain the csa' b'standard itself. in this faq, "cec" really means the' b'appropriate provincial standard. in particular, this faq is' b'derived from the ontario hydro electrical safety code, 20th' b'edition which is in turn based on csa c22.1-1990 (16th' b'edition). while differences exist between the provinces, an' b'attempt has been made to avoid specific-to-ontario detail.' b'' b'the appropriate provincial code can be obtained from electrical' b'inspection offices of your provincial power authority. in' b"ontario, it's ontario hydro. the ontario hydro book isn't" b"overly fat. it's about c$25, and includes mailed updates. i" b'hear that these standards are somewhat easier to read than the' b'equivalent nec publications.' b'' b"don't bother asking in quebec diy wiring is banned throughout" b'the province.' b'' b'' b'in most places, homeowners are allowed to do their own wiring.' b"in some, they're not. check with your local electrical" b"inspector. most places won't permit you to do wiring on other's" b'homes for money without a license. nor are you permitted to do' b'wiring in "commercial" buildings. multiple dwellings (eg: duplexes)' b'are usually considered "semi-commercial" or "commercial". however,' b'many jurisdictions will permit you to work on semi-commercial' b"wiring if you're supervised by a licensed electrician if you can" b'find one willing to supervise.' b'' b'if you do your own wiring, an important point:' b'' b'do it neat and well! what you really want to aim for is a better' b"job than an electrician will do. after all, it's your own home," b"and it's you or your family that might get killed if you make" b'a mistake. an electrician has time pressures, has the skills' b'and knows the tricks of the trade to do a fast, safe job.' b"in this faq we've consciously given a few recommendations that" b"are in excess of code, because we feel that it's reasonable," b'and will impress the inspector.' b'' b"the inspector will know that you're an amateur. you have to" b'earn his trust. the best way of doing this is to spend your' b"time doing as neat a job as possible. don't cut corners." b'exceed specifications. otherwise, the inspector may get extremely' b'picky and fault you on the slightest transgressions.' b'' b"don't try to hide anything from the inspector." b'' b"use the proper tools. ie: don't use a bread knife to strip" b'wires, or twist wires with your fingers. the inspector' b"won't like it, and the results won't be that safe. and it" b"takes longer. and you're more likely to stick a hunk of" b'12ga wire through your hand that way.' b'' b"don't handle house wire when it's very cold (eg: below -10c" b'or 16f). thermoplastic house wire, particularly older types' b'become very brittle.' b'' b'' b"first, there's the obvious a hammer, a drill, a few" b"screwdrivers, both straight and phillips-head. if you're" b'lucky enough to live in canada (or find a source of csa-approved' b'devices) you need robertson ("square recess") screwdrivers' b'(#1 and instead of phillips.' b'' b'for drilling a few holes, a or spade bit and or' b'3/8" electric drill will do. if you\'re doing a lot, or' b'are working with elderly lumber, we recommend a drill' b'(right-angle drills are wonderful. can be rented) and' b'3/4" or screw-point auger drill bits. these bits pull' b"you through, so they're much faster and less fatiguing, even" b'in year old hardwood timbers.' b'' b'screw-driver bits are useful for drills, expecially if you' b'install your electrical boxes using screws (drywall screws' b'work well).' b'' b'for stripping wire, use a real wire stripper, not a knife or' b'ordinary wire cutters. don\'t buy the k-mart "combo stripper,' b'crimper and bottle opener" types. you should expect to pay' b'$15 to for a good "plier-type" pair. it will have sized' b"stripping holes, and won't nick or grab the wire it should" b'be easy to strip wire with it. one model has a small hole in the' b'blade for forming exact wire loops for screw terminals. there' b"are fancier types (autostrip/cut), but they generally aren't" b"necessary, and pros usually don't use them." b'' b'a pair of diagonal side cutter pliers are useful for clipping ends' b"in constricted places. don't use these for stripping wire." b'' b'you will need linesman pliers for twisting wires for wire nuts.' b'' b'you should have a pair of needle-nose pliers for fiddling' b"inside boxes and closing loops, but it's better to form wire" b'loops with a "loop former hole" on your wire stripper more' b'accurate.' b'' b"if you're using non-metallic cable, get a cable stripper for" b'removing the sheath. or, do what some pros do, they nick the' b'end of the sheath, grab the ground wire with a pair of pliers,' b'and simply rip the sheath back using the ground wire as a' b'"zipper", and cut the sheath off. you shouldn\'t try to strip' b"the sheath with a knife point, because it's too easy to" b'slash the insulation on the conductors. apparently stanley' b'utility knives fitted with linoleum cutters (hooked blades)' b'can be used to strip sheath, but there is still the possibility' b"that you'll gouge the conductors." b'' b"for any substantial amount of work with armored cable, it's well" b'worth your while to invest in a rotary cable splitter (~us$ b'hack saws are tricky to use without cutting into the wire' b'or the insulation.' b'' b'three-prong outlet testers are a quick check for properly-wired' b'outlets. about multimeters tell you more, but are a lot more' b'expensive, and probably not worth it for most people. a simple' b'voltage sensor, which can detect potential through an insulated' b'wire not supplying any devices, is extremely helpful; they cost' b'about us$ at radio shack.' b'' b'you should have a voltage detector to check that the wires are' b'dead before doing work on them. neon-bulb version are cheap b'and work well. if you get more serious, a "audible alarm" type is' b"good for tracing circuits without a helper. (though i've been known" b'to lock the drill on, and hit breakers until the scream stops b'' b'for running wires through existing walls, you need fish tape.' b'often, two tapes are needed, though sometimes, a bent hanger or' b'a length of thin chain will suffice. fish tapes can be rented.' b'' b'electrical tape. lots of it seriously, a good and competent' b'wiring job will need very little tape. the tape is useful for' b'wrapping dicy insulation in repair work. another use is to wrap' b'around the body of outlets and switches to cover the termination' b"screws i don't do this, but drywall contractors prefer it (to" b'prevent explosions when the drywall knife collides with a live outlet' b'that has no cover plate).' b'' b'' b'the ul stands for "underwriters laboratory". it used to be' b'an insurance industry organization, but now it is independent' b'and non-profit. it tests electrical components and equipment' b'for potential hazards. when something is ul-listed, that means' b'that the ul has tested the device, and it meets their requirements' b"for safety ie: fire or shock hazard. it doesn't necessarily" b"mean that the device actually does what it's supposed to, just" b"that it probably won't kill you." b'' b'the ul does not have power of law in the u.s. you are' b'permitted to buy and install non-ul-listed devices. however,' b'insurance policies sometimes have clauses in them that will' b'limit their liability in case of a claim made in response to' b'the failure of a non-ul-listed device. furthermore, in' b'many situations the nec will require that a wiring component' b'used for a specific purpose is ul-listed for that purpose.' b'indirectly, this means that certain parts of your wiring' b'must be ul-listed before an inspector will approve it and/or' b'occupancy permits issued.' b'' b'' b'every electrical device or component must be certified by the' b'canadian standards association before it can be sold in' b'canada. implicit in this is that all wiring must be done' b'with csa-approved materials. they perform testing similar to' b'the ul (a bit more stringent), except that csa approval is' b'required by law.' b'' b'again, like the ul, if a fire was caused by non-csa-approved' b'equipment, your insurance company may not have to pay the' b'claim.' b'' b'in canada, there is a branch organization of the ul, called ulc' b'(ul of canada). ulc does not have power of law, and seems to' b'be more a liason group between the csa and insurance' b'companies.' b'' b'' b'usa: the following three books were suggested by our readers' b'' b'residential wiring' b'by jeff markell,' b'craftsman books,' b'carlsbad ca for isbn b'' b'practical electrical wiring' b'residential, farm and industrial, based on the national' b'electrical code ansi/nfpa b'herbert p. richter and w. creighton schwan' b'mcgraw-hill book co.' b'' b'wiring simplified' b'h. p. richter and w. c. schwan' b'park publishing co.' b'' b'try to make sure that the book is based on the latest nec' b'revision. which is currently b'' b'canada: p.s. knight authors and publishes a book called' b'"electrical code simplified". there appears to be a version' b'published specific to each province, and is very tied into the' b'appropriate provincial code. it focuses on residential wiring,' b"and is indispensible for canadian diy'ers. it is better to get" b'this book than the cec unless you do a lot of wiring (or answer' b'questions on the net b'' b'it is updated each time the provincial codes are. this book is' b'available at all diy and hardware stores for less than c$10.' b'' b'' b'most jurisdictions require that you obtain a permit and' b'inspections of any wiring that is done. amongst other more' b'mundane bureaucratic reasons (like insurance companies not' b'liking to have to pay claims), a permit and inspections' b'provides some assurance that you, your family, your neighbors' b"or subsequent owners of your home don't get killed or lose" b'their homes one night due to a sloppy wiring job.' b'' b'most jurisdictions have the power to order you to vacate your' b'home, or order you to tear out any wiring done without a' b'permit. california, for instance, is particularly nasty about' b'this.' b'' b'if fire starts in your home, and un-inspected wiring is at' b'fault, insurance companies will often refuse to pay the damage' b'claims.' b'' b'in general, the process goes like this:' b'- you apply to your local inspections office or building' b'department for a permit. you should have a sketch or' b'detailed drawing of what you plan on doing. this is' b"a good time to ask questions on any things you're not" b"sure of. if you're doing major work, they may impose" b'special conditions on you, require loading' b'calculations and ask other questions. at this point' b'they will tell you which inspections you will need.' b"- if you're installing a main panel, you will need to" b'have the panel and service connections inspected' b'before your power utility will provide a connection.' b'this is sometimes done by the local power authority' b'rather than the usual inspectors.' b'- after installing the boxes and wiring, but before' b'the insulation/walls go up, you will need a' b'"rough-in" inspection.' b'- after the walls are up, and the wiring is complete,' b'you will need a "final inspection".' b'' b'do i have to upgrade?' b'' b'in general, there is no requirement to upgrade older dwellings,' b'though there are some exceptions (ie: smoke detectors in some' b'cases). however, any new work must be done according to the' b"latest electrical code. also, if you do ``major'' work, you" b'may be required to upgrade certain existing portions or all' b'of your system. check with your local electrical inspector.' b'' b'' b'one thing where things might get a bit confusing is the' b'different numbers people bandy about for the voltage of' b'a circuit. one person might talk about 110v, another 117v' b'or another 120v. these are all, in fact, exactly the same' b'thing... in north america the utility companies are required' b'to supply a split-phase volt feed to your house.' b'this works out as two 120v legs. additionally, since there' b"are resistive voltage drops in the house wiring, it's not" b'unreasonable to find 120v has dropped to 110v or 240v has dropped' b'to 220v by the time the power reaches a wall outlet. especially' b'at the end of an extension cord or long circuit run. for a number' b'of reasons, some historical, some simple personal orneryness,' b'different people choose call them by slightly different numbers.' b'this faq has chosen to be consistent with calling them "110v" and' b'"220v", except when actually saying what the measured voltage will' b'be. confusing? a bit. just ignore it.' b'' b'one thing that might make this a little more understandable' b'is that the nameplates on equipment ofen show the lower (ie: 110v' b'instead of 120v) value. what this implies is that the device' b'is designed to operate properly when the voltage drops that' b'low.' b'' b'208v is *not* the same as 240v. 208v is the voltage between' b'phases of a 3-phase "y" circuit that is 120v from neutral to any' b'hot. 480v is the voltage between phases of a 3-phase "y"' b"circuit that's 277v from hot to neutral." b'' b'in keeping with 110v versus 120v strangeness, motors intended' b'to run on 480v three phase are often labelled as 440v...' b'' b'' b'there are logically four wires involved with supplying the' b'main panel with power. three of them will come from the utility' b'pole, and a fourth (bare) wire comes from elsewhere.' b'' b'the bare wire is connected to one or more long metal bars pounded' b'into the ground, or to a wire buried in the foundation, or sometimes' b'to the water supply pipe (has to be metal, continuous to where' b'the main water pipe entering the house. watch out for galvanic' b'action conductivity "breaks" (often between copper and iron pipe)).' b'this is the "grounding conductor". it is there to make sure that' b'the third prong on your outlets is connected to ground. this wire' b'normally carries no current.' b'' b'one of the other wires will be white (or black with white or' b'yellow stripes, or sometimes simply black). it is the neutral wire.' b'it is connected to the "centre tap" (cec; "center tap" in the' b'nec) of the distribution transformer supplying the power. it' b'is connected to the grounding conductor in only one place (often' b'inside the panel). the neutral and ground should not be connected' b'anywhere else. otherwise, weird and/or dangerous things may happen.' b'' b'furthermore, there should only be one grounding system in' b'a home. some codes require more than one grounding electrode.' b'these will be connected together, or connected to the neutral' b'at a common point still one grounding system. adding additional' b'grounding electrodes connected to other portions of the house' b'wiring is unsafe and contrary to code.' b'' b'if you add a subpanel, the ground and neutral are usually' b'brought as separate conductors from the main panel, and are' b'not connected together in the subpanel (ie: still only one' b'neutral-ground connection). however, in some situations' b'(certain categories of separate buildings) you actually do' b'have to provide a second grounding electrode consult your' b'inspector.' b'' b'the other two wires will usually be black, and are the "hot"' b'wires. they are attached to the distribution transformer as' b'well.' b'' b'the two black wires are degrees out of phase with each' b'other. this means if you connect something to both hot wires,' b'the voltage will be volts. if you connect something to the' b'white and either of the two blacks you will get 110v.' b'' b'some panels seem to only have three wires coming into them.' b'this is either because the neutral and ground are connected' b'together at a different point (eg: the meter or pole) and one' b'wire is doing dual-duty as both neutral and ground, or in some' b'rare occasions, the service has only one hot wire (110v only' b'service).' b'' b'' b'inside the panel, connections are made to the incoming wires.' b'these connections are then used to supply power to selected' b'portions of the home. there are three different combinations:' b'1) one hot, one neutral, and ground: 110v circuit.' b'2) two hots, no neutral, and ground: 220v circuit.' b'3) two hots, neutral, and ground: 220v circuit neutral,' b'and/or two 110v circuits with a common neutral.' b'' b'(1) is used for most circuits supplying receptacles and' b'lighting within your house. is usually used for supplying' b'power to major appliances such as stoves, and dryers they' b'often have need for both 220v and 110v, or for bringing several' b'circuits from the panel box to a distribution point. is' b'usually for special 220v motor circuits, electric heaters, or' b'air conditioners.' b'' b'[note: in the us, the nec frequently permits a circuit similar' b'to be used for stoves and dryers namely, that there' b'are two hot wires, and a wire that does dual duty as neutral' b'and ground, and is connected to the frame as well as providing' b'the neutral for 110v purposes three prong plugs instead' b'of four (*only* for stoves/dryers connected to the main panel.' b'when connected to most sub-panels, prong plugs and receptacles' b'are required). in our not-so-humble opinion this is crazy, but' b'the nfpa claims that this practice was re-evaluated for the nec,' b'and found to be safe. check your local codes, or inquire as to' b'local practice there are restrictions on when this is' b'permissible.]' b'' b'(1) is usually wired with three conductor wire: black for hot,' b'white for neutral, and bare for grounding.' b'' b'(2) and have one hot wire coloured red, the other black, a' b'bare wire for grounding, and in a white wire for neutral.' b'' b'you will sometimes see wired with just a black, white and ground' b'wire. since the white is "hot" in this case, both the nec and cec' b'requires that the white wire be "permanently marked" at the ends' b'to indicate that it is a live wire. usually done with paint, nail' b'polish or sometimes electrical tape.' b'' b'each circuit is attached to the main wires coming into the' b'panel through a circuit breaker or fuse.' b'' b'there are, in a few locales, circuits that look like b'or except that they have two bare ground wires. some places' b'require this for hot tubs and the like (one ground is "frame ground",' b'the other attaches to the motor). this may or may not be an' b'alternative to gfci protection.' b'' b'' b'according to the terminology in the cec and nec, the' b'"grounding" conductor is for the safety ground, i.e., the green' b'or bare wire. the word "neutral" is reserved for the white when' b'you have a circuit with more than one "hot" wire. since the white' b'wire is connected to neutral and the grounding conductor inside the' b'panel, the proper term is "grounded conductor". however, the' b'potential confusion between "grounded conductor" and "grounding' b'conductor" can lead to potentially lethal mistakes you should' b'never use the bare wire as a "grounded conductor" or white wire' b'as the "grounding conductor", even though they are connected' b'together in the panel.' b'' b'[but not in subpanels subpanels are fed neutral and ground' b'separately from the main panel. usually.]' b'' b'in the trade, and in common usage, the word "neutral" is used' b'for "grounded conductor". this faq uses "neutral" simply to' b'avoid potential confusion. we recommend that you use "neutral"' b'too. thus the white wire is always (except in some light' b'switch applications) neutral. not ground.' b'' b'' b'fuses and circuit breakers are designed to interrupt the power' b'to a circuit when the current flow exceeds safe levels. for' b'example, if your toaster shorts out, a fuse or breaker should' b'"trip", protecting the wiring in the walls from melting. as' b'such, fuses and breakers are primarily intended to protect the' b'wiring ul or csa approval supposedly indicates that the' b"equipment itself won't cause a fire." b'' b'fuses contain a narrow strip of metal which is designed to melt' b'(safely) when the current exceeds the rated value, thereby' b'interrupting the power to the circuit. fuses trip relatively' b'fast. which can sometimes be a problem with motors which have' b'large startup current surges. for motor circuits, you can use' b'a "time-delay" fuse (one brand is "fusetron") which will avoid' b'tripping on momentary overloads. a fusetron looks like a' b'spring-loaded fuse. a fuse can only trip once, then it must be' b'replaced.' b'' b'breakers are fairly complicated mechanical devices. they' b'usually consist of one spring loaded contact which is latched' b'into position against another contact. when the current flow' b'through the device exceeds the rated value, a bimetallic strip' b'heats up and bends. by bending it "trips" the latch, and the' b'spring pulls the contacts apart. circuit breakers behave' b'similarly to fusetrons that is, they tend to take longer to' b'trip at moderate overloads than ordinary fuses. with high' b'overloads, they trip quickly. breakers can be reset a finite' b'number of times each time they trip, or are thrown' b'when the circuit is in use, some arcing takes place, which' b'damages the contacts. thus, breakers should not be used in' b'place of switches unless they are specially listed for the' b'purpose.' b'' b'neither fuses nor breakers "limit" the current per se. a dead' b'short on a circuit can cause hundreds or sometimes even' b'thousands of amperes to flow for a short period of time, which' b'can often cause severe damage.' b'' b'' b'statistics show that fuse panels have a significantly higher' b'risk of causing a fire than breaker panels. this is usually' b'due to the fuse being loosely screwed in, or the contacts' b'corroding and heating up over time, or the wrong size fuse' b'being installed, or the proverbial "replace the fuse with a' b'penny" trick.' b'' b'since breakers are more permanently installed, and have better' b'connection mechanisms, the risk of fire is considerably less.' b'' b'fuses are prone to explode under extremely high overload. when' b'a fuse explodes, the metallic vapor cloud becomes a conducting' b'path. result? from complete meltdown of the electrical panel,' b'melted service wiring, through fires in the electrical' b'distribution transformer and having your house burn down.' b"breakers don't do this." b'' b'many jurisdictions, particularly in canada, no longer permit' b'fuse panels in new installations. the nec does permit new' b'fuse panels in some rare circumstances (requiring the special' b'inserts to "key" the fuseholder to specific size fuses)' b'' b'some devices, notably certain large air conditioners, require fuse' b'protection in addition to the breaker at the panel. the fuse' b'is there to protect the motor windings from overload. check the' b'labeling on the unit. this is usually only on large permanently' b'installed motors. the installation instructions will tell you' b'if you need one.' b'' b'' b'for a amp circuit, use gauge wire. for a amp circuit,' b'you can use gauge wire (in most locales). for a long run,' b'though, you should use the next larger size wire, to avoid' b'voltage drops. gauge is only slightly more expensive than' b"14 gauge, though it's stiffer and harder to work with." b'' b"here's a quick table for normal situations. go up a size for" b'more than foot runs, when the cable is in conduit, or' b"ganged with other wires in a place where they can't dissipate" b'heat easily:' b'' b'gauge\t\tamps' b'14\t\t15' b'12\t\t20' b'10\t\t30' b'8\t\t40' b'6\t\t65' b'' b"we don't list bigger sizes because it starts getting very dependent" b'on the application and precise wire type.' b'' b'' b'there are two considerations, voltage drop and heat buildup.' b'the smaller the wire is, the higher the resistance is. when' b'the resistance is higher, the wire heats up more, and there is' b'more voltage drop in the wiring. the former is why you need' b'higher-temperature insulation and/or bigger wires for use in' b'conduit; the latter is why you should use larger wire for long' b'runs.' b'' b'neither effect is very significant over very short distances.' b'there are some very specific exceptions, where use of smaller' b'wire is allowed. the obvious one is the line cord on most' b"lamps. don't try this unless you're certain that your use fits" b'one of those exceptions; you can never go wrong by using larger' b'wire.' b'' b'' b'this is used to describe the size and quantity of conductors' b'in a cable. the first number specifies the gauge. the second' b'the number of current carrying conductors in the wire but' b'remember there\'s usually an extra ground wire. means' b'14 gauge, two insulated current carrying wires, plus bare ground.' b'' b'-2 wire usually has a black, white and bare ground wire. sometimes' b'the white is red instead for 220v circuits without neutral. in' b'the latter case, the sheath is usually red too.' b'' b'-3 wire usually has a black, red, white and bare ground wire.' b'usually carrying 220v with neutral.' b'' b'used?' b'' b"a wire nut is a cone shaped threaded plastic thingummy that's used" b'to connect wires together. "marrette" or "marr connector"' b"are trade names. you'll usually use a lot of them in diy wiring." b'' b'in essence, you strip the end of the wires about an inch, twist them' b'together, then twist the wirenut on.' b'' b"though some wirenuts advertise that you don't need to twist the" b"wire, do it anyways it's more mechanically and electrically" b'secure.' b'' b'there are many different sizes of wire nut. you should check' b"that the wire nut you're using is the correct size for the" b"quantity and sizes of wire you're connecting together." b'' b"don't just gimble the wires together with a pair of pliers or" b'your fingers. use a pair of blunt nose ("linesman") pliers,' b'and carefully twist the wires tightly and neatly. sometimes' b"it's a good idea to trim the resulting end to make sure it" b'goes in the wirenut properly.' b'' b'some people wrap the "open" end of the wirenut with electrical' b'tape. this is probably not a good idea the inspector may' b"tear it off during an inspection. it's usually done because" b'a bit of bare wire is exposed outside the wire nut instead' b'of taping it, the connection should be redone.' b'' b'' b"a gfci is a ``ground-fault circuit interrupter''. it measures" b'the current current flowing through the hot wire and the' b'neutral wire. if they differ by more than a few milliamps, the' b'presumption is that current is leaking to ground via some other' b'path. this may be because of a short circuit to the chassis of' b'an appliance, or to the ground lead, or through a person. any' b'of these situations is hazardous, so the gfci trips, breaking' b'the circuit.' b'' b'gfcis do not protect against all kinds of electric shocks. if,' b'for example, you simultaneously touched the hot and neutral' b'leads of a circuit, and no part of you was grounded, a gfci' b"wouldn't help. all of the current that passed from the hot" b'lead into you would return via the neutral lead, keeping the' b'gfci happy.' b'' b'the two pairs of connections on a gfci outlet are not symmetric.' b'one is labeled load; the other, line. the incoming power feed' b'*must* be connected to the line side, or the outlet will not be' b'protected. the load side can be used to protect all devices' b'downstream from it. thus, a whole string of outlets can be' b'covered by a single gfci outlet.' b'' b'' b'the nec mandates gfcis for 110v, 15a or 20a single phase' b"outlets, in bathrooms, kitchens within of the sink, garages," b'unfinished basements or crawl spaces, outdoors, near a pool, or' b"just about anywhere else where you're likely to encounter water" b'or dampness. there are exceptions for inaccessible outlets,' b"those dedicated to appliances ``occupying fixed space''," b'typically refrigerators and freezers, and for sump pumps and' b'laundry appliances.' b'' b'the cec does not mandate as many gfcis. in particular, there' b'is no requirement to protect kitchen outlets, or most garage or' b'basement outlets. basement outlets must be protected if you' b"have a dirt floor, garage outlets if they're near the door to" b'outside. bathrooms and most exterior outlets must have gfcis.' b'' b'even if you are not required to have gfci protection, you may' b'want to consider installing it anyway. unless you need a gfci' b'breaker (see below), the cost is low. in the u.s., gfci' b'outlets can cost as little as us$8. (costs are a bit higher in' b'canada: c$12.) evaluate your own risk factors. does your' b'finished basement ever get wet? do you have small children?' b'do you use your garage outlets to power outdoor tools? does' b'water or melted snow ever puddle inside your garage?' b'' b'' b"gfcis are generally not used on circuits that (a) don't pose a" b'safety risk, and (b) are used to power equipment that must run' b'unattended for long periods of time. refrigerators, freezers,' b'and sump pumps are good examples. the rationale is that gfcis' b'are sometimes prone to nuisance trips. some people claim that' b'the inductive delay in motor windings can cause a momentary' b'current imbalance, tripping the gfci. note, though, that most' b"gfci trips are real; if you're getting a lot of trips for no" b"apparent reason, you'd be well-advised to check your wiring" b'before deciding that the gfci is broken or useless.' b'' b'' b'for most situations, you can use either a gfci outlet as the' b'first device on the circuit, or you can install a breaker with' b'a built-in gfci. the former is generally preferred, since gfci' b'breakers are quite expensive. for example, an ordinary ge' b'breaker costs ~us$5; the gfci model costs ~us$35. there is one' b'major exception: if you need to protect a ``multi-wire branch' b"circuit'' (two or more circuits sharing a common neutral wire)," b"such as a canadian-style kitchen circuit, you'll need a" b'multi-pole gfci breaker. unfortunately, these are expensive;' b'the cost can range into the hundreds of dollars, depending on' b'what brand of panel box you have. but if you must protect such' b'a circuit (say, for a pool heater), you have no choice.' b'' b'one more caveat gfci outlets are bulky. you may want to use' b'an oversize box when installing them. on second thought, use' b"large (actually deep) boxes everywhere. you'll thank yourself for it." b'' b"incidentally, if you're installing a gfci to ensure that one" b"specific outlet is protected (such as a bathroom), you don't" b'really have to go to all of the trouble to find the first' b'outlet in the circuit, you could simply find the first outlet' b'in the bathroom, and not gfci anything upstream of it. but' b'protecting the whole circuit is preferred.' b'' b"when you install a gfci, it's a good idea to use the little" b'"ground fault protected" stickers that come with it and mark' b'the outlets downstream of the gfci. you can figure out which' b'outlets are "downstream", simply by tripping the gfci with the' b'test button and see which outlets are dead.' b'' b'' b"apart from their use in electronics, which we won't comment on," b"and for certain fluorescent lights (they won't turn on without" b"a good ground connection), they're intended to guard against" b'insulation failures within the device. generally, the case of' b"the appliance is connected to the ground lead. if there's an" b'insulation failure that shorts the hot lead to the case, the' b'ground lead conducts the electricity away safely (and possibly' b'trips the circuit breaker in the process). if the case is not' b'grounded and such a short occurs, the case is live and if' b"you touch it while you're grounded, you'll get zapped. of" b'course, if the circuit is gfci-protected, it will be a very' b'tiny zap which is why you can use gfcis to replace' b'ungrounded outlets (both nec and cec).' b'' b'there are some appliances that should *never* be grounded. in' b'particular, that applies to toasters and anything else with' b'exposed conductors. consider: if you touch the heating' b"electrode in a toaster, and you're not grounded, nothing will" b"happen. if you're slightly grounded, you'll get a small shock;" b'the resistance will be too high. but if the case were' b"grounded, and you were holding it, you'd be the perfect path to" b'ground...' b'' b'' b'nowadays, many two-prong devices have one prong wider than the' b'other. this is so that the device could rely (not guaranteed!)' b'on one specific wire being neutral, and the other hot.' b'this is particularly advantageous in light fixtures, where the' b'the shell should neutral (safety), or other devices which want to' b'have an approximate ground reference (ie: some radios).' b'' b'most 2-prong extension cords have wide prongs too.' b'' b'this requires that you wire your outlets and plugs the right' b'way around. you want the wide prong to be neutral, and the' b'narrow one hot. most outlets have a darker metal for the' b'hot screw, and lighter coloured screw for the neutral.' b'if not, you can usually figure out which is which by which' b'prong the terminating screw connects to.' b'' b'' b'the nec requires at least two amp ``small appliance' b"circuits'' for kitchens. the cec requires split-duplex" b'receptacles. outlets must be installed such that no point is more' b'than (nec) mm cec) from an outlet. every counter wider' b'than (nec) or mm (cec) must have at least one outlet.' b'the circuit these outlets are on may not feed any outlets except' b'in the kitchen, pantry, or dining room. furthermore, these circuits' b'are in addition to any required for refrigerators, stoves, microwaves,' b"lighting, etc. non-dedicated outlets within of a sink *must* be" b'protected by a gfci (nec only).' b'' b'split duplex receptacles are fed with a 220v circuit. the tab' b'is broken on the hot side of the outlet, and one hot goes to' b'the upper outlet, and the other hot goes to the lower outlet.' b'the neutral connects to both outlets through one screw. when' b'"carrying through" to another outlet, the neutral must be' b'pigtailed, such that removing the outlet, or having the neutral' b"connection fall off doesn't cause the neutral to disconnect" b'from downstream outlets.' b'' b'' b'there must be at least one outlet in each bathroom, adjacent to' b'the sink, in addition to any outlet that may be incorporated in' b'the light fixture. all such outlets *must* be gfci-protected.' b'' b'' b'romex is a brand name for a type of plastic insulated wire.' b'sometimes called non-metallic sheath. the formal name is nm.' b'this is suitable for use in dry, protected areas (ie: inside' b'stud walls, on the sides of joists etc.), that are not subject' b'to mechanical damage or excessive heat. most newer homes are' b'wired almost exclusively with nm wire. there are several' b'different categories of nm cable.' b'' b'bx cable technically known as armored cable or "ac" has a' b'flexible aluminum or steel sheath over the conductors and is' b'fairly resistant to damage.' b'' b'teck cable is ac with an additional external thermoplastic' b'sheath.' b'' b'protection for cable in concealed locations: where nm or ac cable' b'is run through studs, joists or similar wooden members, the outer' b'surface of the cable must be kept at least 32mm/1.25" (cec nec)' b'from the edges of the wooden members, or the cable should be protected' b'from mechanical injury. this latter protection can take the form of' b'metal plates (such as spare outlet box ends) or conduit.' b'' b'[note: inspector-permitted practise in canada suggests that armored' b'cable, or flexible conduit can be used as the mechanical protection,' b'but this is technically illegal.]' b'' b'additional protection recommendations (these are rules in the' b'canadian codes they are reasonable answers to the vague' b'references to "exposed to mechanical damage" in both the nec' b'and cec):' b'' b'- nm cable should be protected against mechanical damage' b'where it passes through floors or on the surface of walls' b'in exposed locations under feet from the floor.' b'ie: use ac instead, flexible conduit, wooden guards etc.' b'- where cable is suspended, as in, connections to furnaces' b'or water heaters, the wire should be protected. canadian' b'practise is usually to install a junction or outlet' b'box on the wall, and use a short length of ac cable' b'or nm cable in flexible conduit to "jump" to the appliance.' b'stapling nm to a piece of lumber is also sometimes used.' b'- where nm cable is run in close proximity to heating' b'ducts or pipe, heat transfer should be minimized by' b'means of a 25mm/1" air space, or suitable insulation' b'material (a wad of fiberglass).' b"- nm cable shall be supported within 300mm/1' of every box" b"or fitting, and at intervals of no more than 1.5m/5'." b'holes in joists or studs are considered "supports".' b'some slack in the cable should be provided adjacent to' b'each box. [while fishing cable is technically in violation,' b'it is permitted where "proper" support is impractical]' b'- conductor nm cable should never be stapled on edge.' b'[knight also insists on only one cable per staple, referring' b'to the "workmanship" clause, but this seems more honoured' b'in the breach...]' b'- cable should never be buried in plaster, cement or' b'similar finish.' b'- cable should be pr