different requirements for mobile homes.' b"check your local codes, *especially* if you're doing anything" b"that's the slightest out of the ordinary." b'' b'wire selection table (incomplete the real tables are enormous,' b'uncommon wire types or applications omitted)' b'' b'condition\t\t\ttype\tcec\tnec' b'' b'exposed/concealed dry\t\tplastic\tnmd90\tnm' b'armor\tac90\tac' b'teck90' b'' b'exposed/concealed damp\t\tplastic\tnmd90\tnmc' b'armor\tacwu90' b'teck90' b'' b'exposed/concealed wet\t\tplastic\tnmwu90' b'armor\tacwu90' b'teck90' b'' b'exposed to weather\t\tplastic\tnmwu' b'tw etc.' b'armor\tteck90' b'' b'direct earth burial/\t\tplastic\tnmwu*\tuf' b'service entrance\t\t\trwu' b'twu' b'armor\tra90' b'teck90' b'acwu90' b'[* nmwu not for service entrance]' b'' b'' b'the nec permits use of plastic boxes with non-metallic cable' b'only. the reasoning is simple with armored cable, the box' b'itself provides ground conductor continuity. u.s. plastic' b"boxes don't use metal cable clamps." b'' b'the cec is slightly different. the cec never permits cable' b'armor as a grounding conductor. however, you must still' b'provide ground continuity for metallic sheath. the cec also' b'requires grounding of any metal cable clamps on plastic boxes.' b'' b'the advantage of plastic boxes is comparatively minor even for' b'non-metallic sheathed cable you can avoid making one ground' b'connection and they sometimes cost a little less. on the other' b'hand, plastic boxes are more vulnerable to impacts. for' b'exposed or shop wiring, metal boxes are probably better.' b'' b'' b'a junction box is a box used only for connecting wires together.' b'' b"junction boxes must be located in such a way that they're accessible" b'later. ie: not buried under plaster. excessive use of junction' b'boxes is often a sign of sloppy installation, and inspectors may' b'get nasty.' b'' b'' b'in general, one can replace fixtures freely, subject to a few' b'caveats. first, of course, one should check the amperage' b'rating of the circuit. if your heart is set on installing half' b'a dozen watt floodlights, you may need to run a new wire' b'back to the panel box. but there are some more subtle' b'constraints as well. for example, older house' b"wiring doesn't have high-temperature insulation. the excess" b'heat generated by a ceiling-mounted lamp can and will cause the' b'insulation to deteriorate and crack, with obvious bad results.' b'some newer fixtures are specifically marked for high' b'temperature wire only. (you may find, in fact, that your' b'ceiling wiring already has this problem, in which case' b'replacing any devices is a real adventure.)' b'' b'other concerns include providing a suitable ground for some' b'fluorescent fixtures, and making sure that the ceiling box and' b'its mounting are strong enough to support the weight of a heavy' b'chandelier or ceiling fan. you may need to install a new box' b'specifically listed for this purpose. a 2x4 across the ceiling' b'joists makes a good support. metal brackets are also available' b'that can be fished into ceilings thru the junction box hole and' b'mounted between the joists.' b'' b'there are special rules for recessed light fixtures such as' b'"pot" lamps or heat lamps. when these are installed in insulated' b'ceilings, they can present a very substantial fire hazard.' b'the cec provides for the installation of pot lamps in insulated' b'ceilings, provided that the fixture is boxed in a "coffin" (usually' b'8\'x16"x12" made by making a pair of joists high, and covering' b"with plywood) that doesn't have any insulation. (yes, that's *feet*" b'long)' b'' b'nec rules are somewhat less stringent. they require at least b'clearance between the fixture and any sort of thermal insulation.' b'the rules also say that one should not obstruct free air movement,' b"which means that a cec-style ``coffin'' might be worthwhile." b"presumably, that's up to the local inspector. [the cec doesn't" b'actually mandate the coffin per-se, this seems to be an inspector' b"requirement to make absolutely certain that the fixture can't get" b'accidentally buried in insulation. ie: if you have insulation blown' b'in later.]' b'' b'there are now fixtures that contain integral thermal cutouts and' b'fairly large cases that can be buried directly in insulation. they are' b'usually limited to watt bulbs, and are unfortunately, somewhat' b'more expensive than the older types. before you use them, you should' b'ensure that they have explicit ul or csa approval for such uses.' b'follow the installation instructions carefully; the prescribed location' b'for the sensor can vary.' b'' b'there does not yet appear to be a heat lamp fixture that is approved' b'for use in insulation. the "coffin" appears the only legal approach.' b'' b'' b'this usually means that the neutral wire in the panel is' b'loose. depending on the load balance, one hot wire may end up' b'being more than 110v, and the other less than 110v, with' b'respect to ground. this is a very hazardous situation it can' b'destroy your electronic equipment, possibly start fires, and in' b'some situations electrocute you (ie: some us jurisdictions' b'require the stove frame connected to neutral).' b'' b'if this happens, contact your electrical authority immediately' b'and have them come and check out the problem.' b'' b'note: a brief second) brightening is sometimes normal with' b'lighting and motors on the same 220v with neutral circuit. a' b'loose main panel neutral will usually show increased brightness' b'far longer than one second. in case of doubt, get help.' b'' b'' b'three phase power has three "hot" wires, degrees out of' b'phase with each other. these are usually used for large motors' b'because it is more "efficient", provides a bit more starting torque,' b'and because the motors are simpler and hence cheaper.' b'' b"you're most likely to encounter a phase circuit that shows" b'110 volts between any hot and ground, and volts between' b'any two hots. the latter shows the difference between a normal' b'220v/110v common neutral circuit, which is volts between the' b'two hots. there are phase circuits with different voltages.' b'' b'bringing in a phase feed to your house is usually' b'ridiculously expensive, or impossible. if the equipment you' b'want to run has a standard motor mount, it is *much* cheaper to' b'buy a new 110v or 220v motor for it. in some cases it is' b'possible to run phase equipment on ordinary power if you have' b'a "capacitor start" unit, or use a larger motor as a' b'(auto-)generator. these are tricky, but are a good solution if' b'the motor is non-standard size, or too expensive or too big to' b"replace. the taunton press book ``the small shop'' has an" b'article on how to do this if you must.' b'' b'note that you lose any possible electrical efficiency by using' b'such a converter. the laws of thermodynamics guarantee that.' b'' b'' b"theoretically, it doesn't make any difference. however, there" b'is a difference is the amount of power lost in the supply' b'wiring. all things being equal, a 220v motor will lose times' b'less power in the house wiring than a 110v motor. this also' b'means that the startup surge loss will be less, and the motor' b'will get to speed quicker. and in some circumstances, the' b'smaller power loss will lead to longer motor life.' b'' b'this is usually irrelevant unless the supply wires are more' b'than feet long.' b'' b'' b'it is a universal physical law that hp is equal to b'watts. given heating loss, power factor and other inefficiencies,' b'it is usually best to consider hp is going to need b'watts. a 110v 15a circuit can only deliver watts to a motor,' b'so it cannot possibly be more than approximately hp. given rational' b'efficiency factors, 1.5hp is more like it.' b'' b'some equipment manufacturers (sears in particular, most router' b'manufacturers in general advertise a hp rating that is far' b'in excess of what is possible. they are giving you a "stall' b'horsepower" or similar. that means the power is measured when' b'the motor is just about to stop turning because of the load.' b"what they don't mention is that if you kept it in that" b'condition for more than a few seconds hopefully your breaker' b"will trip, otherwise the motor will melt it's drawing far" b'more current than it can continuously.' b'' b'when comparing motors, compare the continuous horsepower. this' b"should be on the motor nameplate. if you can't find that figure," b'check the amperage rating, which is always present.' b'' b'' b'older homes frequently have two-prong receptacles instead' b'of the more modern three. these receptacles have no safety' b'ground, and the cabling usually has no ground wire. neither' b'the nec or cec permits installing new prong receptacles anymore.' b'' b'there are several different approaches to solving this:' b'1) if the wiring is done through conduit or bx, and the' b'conduit is continuous back to the panel, you can connect' b'the third prong of a new receptacle to the receptacle' b'box. nec mainly cec frowns on this practise.' b'2) if there is a copper cold water pipe going nearby, and' b"it's continuous to the main house ground point, you can" b'run a conductor to it from the third prong.' b'3) run a ground conductor back to the main panel.' b'4) easiest: install a gfci receptacle. the ground lug' b'should not be connected to anything, but the gfci' b'protection itself will serve instead. the gfci' b'will also protect downstream (possibly also two prong' b'outlets). if you do this to protect downstream outlets,' b'the grounds must not be connected together. since it' b"wouldn't be connected to a real ground, a wiring fault" b'could energize the cases of prong devices connected' b"to other outlets. be sure, though, that there aren't" b'indirect ground plug connections, such as via the sheath' b'on bx cable.' b'' b'the cec permits you to replace a two prong receptacle with a three' b'prong if you fill the u ground with a non-conducting goop.' b'like caulking compound. this is not permitted in the nec.' b'' b'should the test button work?' b'' b"we're sure about what the nec and cec say. remember, though," b"that your local codes may vary. as for the test button there's" b'a resistor connecting the load side of the hot wire to the line' b'side of the neutral wire when you press the test button. current' b'through this resistor shows up as an imbalance, and trips the gfci.' b"this is a simple, passive, and reliable test, and doesn't require" b'a real ground to work. if your gfci does not trip when you press' b'the test button, it is very probably defective or miswired. again:' b"if the test button doesn't work, something's broken, and potentially" b'dangerous. the problem should be corrected immediately.' b'' b'the instructions that come with some gfcis specify that the ground' b'wire must be connected. we do not know why they say this. the' b'causes may be as mundane as an old instruction sheet, or with the' b'formalities of ul or csa listing perhaps the device was never' b'tested without the ground wire being connected. on the other hand,' b'ul or csa approval should only have been granted if the device' b'behaves properly in *all* listed applications, including ungrounded' b'outlet replacement. (one of us called leviton; their gfcis are' b'labeled for installation on grounded circuits only. the technician' b'was surprised to see that; he agreed that the nec does not require' b'it, and promised to investigate.)' b'' b'' b'as with any other kind of wiring, you need enough power for all' b'devices that will be on simultaneously. the code specifies' b'that you should stay under of the nominal capacity of the' b'circuit. for typical home shop use, this means one circuit for' b'the major power tools, and possibly one for a dust collector or' b'shop vac. use at least gauge wire many power tools have' b'big motors, with a big start-up surge. if you can, use amp' b'breakers (nec), though cec requires standard 20a receptacles' b'which means you\'d have to "replug" all your equipment. lights' b'should either be on a circuit of their own and not shared' b'with circuits in the rest of the house or be on at least two' b'separate circuits. the idea is that you want to avoid a' b'situation where a blade is still spinning at several thousand' b"rpm, while you're groping in the dark for the off switch." b'' b"do install lots of outlets. it's easier to install them in the" b"beginning, when you don't have to cut into an existing cable." b"it's useful if at least two circuits are accessible at each" b'point, so you can run a shop vac or a compressor at the same' b'time as the tool you really want. but use metal boxes and' b'plates, and maybe even metal-sheathed cable; you may have' b'objects flying around at high speeds if something goes a bit' b'wrong.' b'' b'note that some jurisdictions have a "no horizontal wiring"' b'rule in workshops or other unfinished areas that are used' b'for working. what this means is that all wiring must be' b'run along structural members. ie: stapled to studs.' b'' b'other possible shop circuits include heater circuits, 220v' b'circuits for some large tools, and air compressor circuits.' b"don't overload circuits, and don't use extension cords if you" b"can help it, unless they're rated for high currents. (a coiled" b'extension cord is not as safe as a straight length of wire of' b"the same gauge. also, the insulation won't withstand as much" b'heat, and heat dissipation is the critical issue.)' b'' b'if your shop is located at some remove from your main panel,' b'you should probably install a subpanel, and derive your shop' b'wiring from it. if you have young children, you may want to' b'equip this panel with a cut-off switch, and possibly a lock.' b"if you want to install individual switches to ``safe''" b'particular circuits, make sure you get ones rated high enough.' b'for example, ordinary light switches are not safely able to' b'handle the start-up surge generated by a table saw. buy' b"``horsepower-rated'' switches instead." b'' b'finally, note that most home shops are in garages or unfinished' b'basements; hence the nec requirements for gfcis apply. and' b"even if you ``know'' that you'd never use one of your shop" b'outlets to run a lawn mower, the next owner of your house might' b'have a different idea.' b'' b'note: fine woodworking magazine often carries articles on shop' b'wiring. april is one place to start.' b'' b'' b'you will need to prepare a trench to specifications, use' b'special wire, protect the wire with conduit or special plastic' b"tubing and possibly lumber (don't use creosoted lumber, it rots" b'thermoplastic insulation and acts as a catalyst in the corrosion' b'of lead). the transition from in-house to underground wire is' b'generally via conduit. all outdoor boxes must be specifically' b'listed for the purpose, and contain the appropriate gaskets,' b'fittings, etc. if the location of the box is subject to immersion' b'in water, a more serious style of water-proof box is needed. and' b"of course, don't forget the gfcis." b'' b'the required depths and other details vary from jurisdiction to' b'jurisdiction, so we suggest you consult your inspector about' b'your specific situation.' b'' b'a hint: buy a roll of bright yellow tape that says "buried power' b'line" and bury it a few inches above where the wire has been placed.' b'' b'' b"during the 1970's, aluminum (instead of copper) wiring became" b'quite popular and was extensively used. since that time,' b'aluminum wiring has been implicated in a number of house fires,' b'and most jurisdictions no longer permit it in new installations.' b"we recommend, even if you're allowed to, that do not use it for new" b'wiring.' b'' b"but don't panic if your house has aluminum wiring. aluminum" b'wiring, when properly installed, can be just as safe as copper.' b'aluminum wiring is, however, very unforgiving of improper' b'installation. we will cover a bit of the theory behind potential' b'problems, and what you can do to make your wiring safe.' b'' b'the main problem with aluminum wiring is a phenomenon known as' b'"cold creep". when aluminum wiring warms up, it expands. when' b'it cools down, it contracts. unlike copper, when aluminum goes' b'through a number of warm/cool cycles it loses a bit of tightness each' b'time. to make the problem worse, aluminum oxidises, or corrodes' b'when in contact with certain types of metal, so the resistance' b'of the connection goes up. which causes it to heat up and corrode/' b'oxidize still more. eventually the wire may start getting very hot,' b"melt the insulation or fixture it's attached to, and possibly even" b'cause a fire.' b'' b'since people usually encounter aluminum wiring when they move' b"into a house built during the 70's, we will cover basic points of" b"safe aluminum wiring. we suggest that, if you're considering purchasing" b'a home with aluminum wiring, or have discovered it later, that you' b'hire a licensed electrician or inspector to check over the wiring' b'for the following things:' b'' b'1) fixtures (eg: outlets and switches) directly attached to' b'aluminum wiring should be rated for it. the device will' b'be stamped with "al/cu" or "co/alr". the latter supersedes' b'the former, but both are safe. these fixtures are somewhat' b'more expensive than the ordinary ones.' b'' b'2) wires should be properly connected (at least way around' b'the screw in a clockwise direction). connections should be' b'tight. while repeated tightening of the screws can make the' b'problem worse, during the inspection it would pay off to snug' b'up each connection.' b'' b'note that aluminum wiring is still often used for the' b'main service entrance cable. it should be inspected.' b'' b'3) "push-in" terminals are an extreme hazard with aluminum wire.' b'any connections using push-in terminals should be redone with' b'the proper screw connections immediately.' b'' b'4) there should be no signs of overheating: darkened connections,' b'melted insulation, or "baked" fixtures. any such damage should' b'be repaired.' b'' b'5) connections between aluminum and copper wire need to be' b'handled specially. current canadian codes require that the' b'wire nut used must be specially marked for connecting' b'aluminum to copper. the nec requires that the wire be' b'connected together using special crimp devices, with an' b'anti-oxidant grease. the tools and materials for the latter' b'are quite expensive not practical to do it yourself unless' b'you can rent the tool.' b'' b'6) any non-rated receptacle can be connected to aluminum wiring' b'by means of a short copper "pigtail". see above.' b'' b'7) shows reasonable workmanship: neat wiring, properly stripped' b'(not nicked) wire etc.' b'' b'if, when considering purchasing a home, an inspection of the wiring' b'shows no problems or only one or two, we believe that you can consider' b'the wiring safe. if there are signs of problems in many places,' b'we suggest you look elsewhere. if the wrong receptacles are used,' b'you can replace them with the proper type, or use pigtails having' b'this professionally done can range from to per receptacle/switch.' b'you can do this yourself too.' b'' b'' b"congratulations. but... it's generally a good idea to hire" b'an inspector to look through the house for hidden gotchas.' b'not just for wiring, but plumbing and structural as well. if an' b'inspection of the wiring shows no problems or only one or two minor' b'ones, we believe that you can consider the wiring safe (after any' b'minor problems are fixed). if there are signs of problems in many' b'places, we suggest you look elsewhere.' b'' b"here's some hints on what to look for:" b'' b'obvious non-code wiring can include:' b'' b'- zip cord wiring, either concealed or nailed to walls' b'- hot wiring on the identified (neutral) conductor without' b'proper marking.' b'- ungrounded grounding outlets (except when downstream of' b'a gfci)' b'- splices hanging in mid-air (other than proper knob-and-tube)' b'- switched neutrals' b'- unsecured romex swinging about like grapevines' b'' b'certain wiring practises that are actually to code (or were at one' b'time) sometimes reveal diy wiring that may have hidden violations:' b'' b'- switches that seem to control nothing (abandoned, perhaps' b'not properly terminated wiring)' b'- a wall switch that shuts off a group of lights that are' b'separately controlled by other wall switches. (except when' b"it's *really* convenient b'- switches and outlets in bizarre locations' b'- great numbers of junction boxes without outlets or lamps' b'- junction boxes with great numbers of wires going into them' b'- wiring that passes through a closet instead of a wall or' b'ceiling' b'- backwrapped grounding wires' b'' b'' b'in the years since edison "invented" electricity, several different' b'wiring "styles" have come and gone. when you buy an older home you' b'may encounter some of this stuff. this section describes the old' b'methods, and some of their idiosyncrasies.' b'' b"the oldest wiring system you're likely to encounter is called" b'"knob and tube" (k&t). it is made up of individual conductors with' b'a cloth insulation. the wires are run along side structural' b'members (eg: joists or studs) using ceramic stand-offs (knobs).' b'wire is run through structural members using ceramic tubes. connections' b'were made by twisting the wire together, soldering, and wrapping' b'with tape. since the hot and neutral were run separately,' b'the wiring tends to be rather confusing. a neutral often runs' b'down the centre of each room, with "taps" off to each fixture.' b'the hot wire tended to run from one fixture to the next. in some' b"cases k&t isn't colour-coded, so the neutral is often the same" b'colour as the hot wires.' b'' b"you'll see k&t in homes built as late as the 40's." b'' b'comments on k&t:' b'' b'- the people installing k&t were pretty paranoid about' b'electricity, so the workmanship tends to be pretty good.' b'- the wire, insulation and insulators tend to stand up' b"very well. most k&t i've seen, for example, is in" b'quite good condition.' b'- no grounding. grounding is usually difficult to install.' b'- boxes are small. receptacle replacement (particularly with' b'gfci) can be difficult. no bushing on boxes either,' b'so wiring changes need special attention to box entry.' b"- sometimes the neutral isn't balanced very well between" b'separately hot circuits, so it is sometimes possible to' b'overload the neutral without exceeding the fusing on' b'any circuit.' b'- building code does not permit insulation in walls' b'that contain k&t.' b'- connection to existing k&t from new circuits can be' b'tricky. consult your inspector.' b'- modern wiring practise requires considerably more' b'outlets to be installed than k&t systems did.' b'' b"since k&t tends to be in pretty decent condition it generally isn't" b"necessary to replace it simply because it's k&t. what you should" b'watch out for is renovations that have interfered with it and' b"be cautious about circuit loading. in many cases it's perfectly" b'reasonable to leave existing k&t alone, and add new fixtures on' b'new circuits using modern techniques.' b'' b'after k&t, they invented multi-conductor cable. the first type' b'you will see is roughly a cloth and varnish insulation. it looks' b'much like the romex cable of the last decade or two. this stuff was' b"used in the 40's and 50's. again, no grounding conductor." b'it was installed much like modern wiring. its major drawback' b"is that this type of insulation embrittles. we've seen whole" b'systems where the insulation would fracture and fall off at' b'a touch. bx cable of the same vintage has similar problems.' b'' b'this stuff is very fragile, and becomes rather hazardous if' b'the wires become bare. this wiring should be left untouched as' b'much as possible whenever an opportunity arises, replace it.' b'a simple receptacle or switch replacement can turn into a several' b'hour long frustrating fight with electrical tape or heat-shrink' b'tubing.' b'' b'after this wiring technique, the more modern romex was invented.' b"it's almost a asphalt impregnated cloth. often a bit sticky." b"this stuff stands up reasonably well and doesn't present a hazard" b'and is reasonably easy to work with. it does not need to be' b'replaced it should be considered as safe as the "modern" stuff b"thermoplastic insulation wire. just don't abuse it too much." b'' b'' b'try to find a proper electrical supply outlet near you. their' b'prices will often be considerably better than chain hardware stores or' b'diy centres, have better quality materials, have wider variety' b'including the "odd" stuff, and have people behind the counter that' b"know what you're talking about. cultivate friendly knowledgeable" b"sales people. they'll give you much valuable information." b'--' 